y research environment.This authoritative and accessible book covers everything from the elements of vector and tensor analysis to ordinary differential equations, special functions, and chaos and fractals. Other topics include integral transforms, complex analysis, and inverse theory; partial differential equations of mathematical geophysics; probability, statistics, and computational methods; and much more.Proven in the classroom, Mathematical Methods for Geophysics and Space Physics features numerous exercises throughout as well as suggestions for further reading.Provides an authoritative and accessible introduction to the subjectCovers vector and tensor analysis, ordinary differential equations, integrals and approximations, Fourier transforms, diffusion and dispersion, sound waves and perturbation theory, randomness in data, and a host of other topicsFeatures numerous exercises throughoutIdeal for students and researchers alikeAn online illustration package is available to professors  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCosmic physicsxMathematics. 0aGeophysicsxMathematics. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Geophysics.2bisacsh  aAnalytical mechanics.  aApplied mathematics.  aAtmospheric physics.  aBessel function.  aBifurcation theory.  aCalculation.  aCalculus of variations.  aCartesian coordinate system.  aCauchy's theorem (geometry).  aCelestial mechanics.  aCentral limit theorem.  aChaos theory.  aClassical electromagnetism.  aClassical mechanics.  aClassical physics.  aConvolution theorem.  aDeformation (mechanics).  aDegeneracy (mathematics).  aDiagram (category theory).  aDifferential equation.  aDrag (physics).  aEarth science.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aEinstein notation.  aElliptic integral.  aElliptic orbit.  aEquation.  aExpectation value (quantum mech